{{for|the gangsta rap group|Death Threat (hip hop group)}} {{multiple issues| {{essay-like|date=February 2015}} {{refimprove|date=December 2010}} }}
A '''death threat''' is a [[threat]], often made [[Anonymity|anonymously]], by one person or a group of people to kill another person or group of people. These threats are often designed to [[intimidate]] victims in order to [[Psychological manipulation|manipulate]] their behaviour, and thus a death threat can be a form of [[coercion]]. For example, a death threat could be used to dissuade a public figure from pursuing a criminal investigation or an advocacy campaign.
In most jurisdictions, death threats are a serious type of [[criminal offence]]. Death threats are often covered by coercion statutes. For instance, the coercion statute in [[Alaska]] says: {{quote|text=A person commits the crime of coercion if the person compels another to engage in conduct from which there is a legal right to abstain or abstain from conduct in which there is a legal right to engage, by means of instilling in the person who is compelled a fear that, if the demand is not complied with, the person who makes the demand or another may inflict physical injury on anyone....<ref>[http://www.touchngo.com/lglcntr/akstats/Statutes/Title11/Chapter41/Section530.htm Alaska Statute 11.41.530(a)(1)]</ref>}}
==Methods== A death threat can be communicated via a wide range of media, among these letters, [[newspaper]] publications, [[telephone call]]s, [[blog|internet blogs]]<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/6499095.stm ''Blog death threats spark debate''] [[BBC News]] retrieved September 30, 2007</ref> and [[e-mail]]. If the threat is made against a political figure, it can also be considered [[treason]]. If a threat is against a non-living location that frequently contains living individuals (e.g. a building), it could be a [[Terrorism|terrorist threat]]. Sometimes, death threats are part of a wider campaign of abuse targeting a person or a group of people (see [[terrorism]], [[mass murder]]).
==Against a head of state== In some [[Monarchy|monarchies]] and [[republic]]s, both democratic and authoritarian, threatening to kill the [[head of state]] and/or [[head of government]] (such as the [[sovereign]], [[Threatening the President of the United States|president]], or [[prime minister]]), is considered a crime, for which punishments vary. The United States law provides for up to five years in prison for threatening any type of [[threatening government officials of the United States|government official]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = 18 U.S. Code § 871 - Threats against President and successors to the Presidency {{!}} US Law {{!}} LII / Legal Information Institute|url = https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/871|website = www.law.cornell.edu|accessdate = 2015-08-13}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom]], under the [[Treason Felony Act 1848]], it is illegal to attempt to kill or deprive the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|monarch]] of his/her throne; this offense was originally punished with [[penal transportation]], and then was changed to the [[death penalty]], and currently the penalty is [[life imprisonment]].
==Osman warning, letter or notice== Named after a high-profile case, ''[[Osman v United Kingdom]]'', these are warnings of death threat or high risk of murder that are issued by British police or legal authorities to the possible victim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thescottishsun.co.uk/scotsol/homepage/news/2157509/Dads-death-threat-warning.html |title=Dad's death threat warning |work=[[The Scottish Sun]] |date=2009-01-27 |accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref> They are used when there is intelligence of the threat, but there is not enough evidence to justify the police arresting the potential murderer.<ref>{{cite web|author=Published on Friday 13 June 2008 17:49 |url=http://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/bed-news/Beds-is-one-of-nations.4185282.jp |title=Beds is one of nation's 'death-threat capitals' - News |publisher=Bedford Today |date=2008-06-13 |accessdate=2012-04-29}}</ref>
