{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}} {{Use British English|date=December 2016}} {{Redirect|Personal Life|The Thermals album|Personal Life (album)}} [[Image:Indian family in Brazil posed in front of hut.jpg|thumb|upright=1.00|Humans traditionally lived in family-based social structures and artificial shelters.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}]] '''Personal life''' is the course of an [[personhood|individual]]'s life, especially when viewed as the sum of personal choices contributing to one's [[identity (social science)|personal identity]].<ref>{{cite book| last1 = Baker| first1 = Maureen| title = Choices and Constraints in Family Life| edition = 2| location = Don Mills, Ontario| publisher = Oxford University Press| publication-date = 2010| page = 1| isbn = 978-0-19-543159-9| quote = In this book, I argue that intimate relationships are certainly influenced by our personal preferences but to a large extent our 'choices' are shaped by family circumstances and events in the wider society [...] }}</ref>
In ancient past, most people's time was limited by the need to meet necessities such as food and shelter and there was not much [[leisure time]]. People identified with their [[social role]] in their community, and engaged in [[job]]s based on necessity rather than personal choice. [[Privacy]] in such communities was rare.
The modern conception of personal life is an offshoot of modern Western society. A modern person tends to distinguish one's work from one's personal life. It is a person's choices and preferences outside work that define personal life, including one's choice of hobbies, cultural interests, manner of dress, and so on. In particular, what activities one engages in during leisure-time defines a person's personal life. For instance, a typical American has about five hours of leisure time per day, more than half of which is spent on watching TV.
People in Western countries, such as the [[United States]], tend to value privacy. Privacy includes both [[information privacy]] and decisional privacy; people expect to be left alone with respect to intimate details of their life and they expect to be free from undue control by others.
==History== [[File:11-stages-womanhood-1840s.jpg|thumb|"The Life & Age of Woman - Stages of Woman's Life from the Cradle to the Grave", 1849]]
In the past, before modern [[technology]] largely alleviated issues of economic [[scarcity]] in industrialised countries, most people spent a large portion of their time attempting to provide their basic survival needs, including water, food, and protection from the weather.<ref name="Van Loon">{{cite book|last= Van Loon|first=Hendrik|title= The Story of Mankind|year= 1921|publisher= Boni and Liveright, Inc.|location= New York|url=http://etext.virginia.edu/toc/modeng/public/VanStor.html}}</ref> Humans needed [[survival skills]] for the sake of both themselves and their community; food needed to be harvested and shelters needed to be maintained.<ref name=Gupta>{{cite journal|last=Gupta |first=Anil K. |title=Origin of agriculture and domestication of plants and animals linked to early Holocene climate amelioration |journal=Current Science |date=10 July 2004 |volume=87 |issue=1 |url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/jul102004/54.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041031122606/http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/jul102004/54.pdf |dead-url=yes |archive-date=31 October 2004 |df= }}</ref> There was little [[privacy]] in a community, and people identified one another according to their social role.<ref name=Barnard>{{cite book|last=Barnard|first=Alan J.|title= Hunter-gatherers in history, archaeology and anthropology|year=2004|publisher= Berg Publishers|isbn= 978-1-85973-825-2}}</ref> [[Labour (economics)|Jobs]] were assigned out of necessity rather than personal choice.<ref name=ERA>{{cite web|title=Why did anthropologists get interested in peasants?|url= http://era.anthropology.ac.uk/Era_Resources/Era/Peasants/intro2.html|work= Experience Rich Anthropology|publisher= University of Kent at Canterbury|accessdate= 26 February 2011}}</ref>
Furthermore, individuals in many [[ancient culture]]s primarily viewed their [[self-existence]] under the aspect of a larger social whole, often one with [[mythological]] underpinnings which placed the individual in relation to the [[cosmos]].<ref name=Percy>{{cite book|last=Percy|first=Walker|title= Lost in the cosmos: the last self-help book|year=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0-312-25399-8|authorlink= Walker Percy}}</ref> People in such cultures found their identity not through their individual [[choice]]s—indeed, they may not have been able to conceive a choice which was purely individual. Such individuals, if asked to describe themselves, would speak of the collective of which they were part: the [[tribe]], the [[Christian Church|Church]], the [[nation]].<ref>{{cite book|last1= Ashton-Jones|first1= Evelyn|title= The Gender reader|year= 1991|publisher= Allyn and Bacon|location= Boston|isbn= 0-205-12806-8|pages=252|author2= Lindholm, Cherry|chapter= Life behind the Veil|author3= Charles Lindholm}}</ref> Even in the 21st century, survival issues dominate in many countries and societies. For example, the continents of Africa and Asia are still largely mired in [[poverty]] and [[third-world]] conditions, without technology, secure shelter, or reliable food sources. In such places, the concepts of a "personal life", "[[self-actualization]]", "personal fulfillment", or "[[privacy]]" are often unaffordable luxuries.<ref name=Maslow>{{cite journal|doi= 10.1037/h0054346|last= Maslow|first= A. H.|title= A Theory of Human Motivation|journal= Psychological Review|year= 1943|volume=50|pages=370–396|url = http://psychclassics.yorku.ca/Maslow/motivation.htm}}</ref>
The English philosopher [[John Locke]] (1632-1704) figures among the pioneers in discussing the concept of [[individual rights]]. In the 17th century he promoted the natural rights of the individual to [[right to life|life]], [[liberty]], and [[property]], and included the [[pursuit of happiness]] as one of the individual's goals.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}
==Sociology== [[File:Gamescom 2009 - Wii (5206).jpg|thumb|Increasingly, leisure time is spent{{by whom?|date=October 2018}} on computer games.]]
The notion of a personal life, as currently understood,{{by whom|date= August 2016}} is in part an artifact of modern Western society. People in the [[United States| United States of America]], especially, place a high value on privacy. Since the [[Colonial history of the United States| colonial period]], commentators have noted Americans' [[individualism]] and their pursuit of [[autonomy| self-definition]].<ref name="de Tocqueville">{{cite book |last= de Tocqueville |first= Alexis |title= Democracy in America |year= 1840 |publisher= Saunders and Otley |location= London |url= http://xroads.virginia.edu/~HYPER/DETOC/home.html }}</ref>{{qn|date= August 2016}}<ref> Compare: {{cite book | last1 = Schleifer | first1 = James T. | author-link1 = James T. Schleifer | chapter = 5: How Does Democracy Threaten Liberty? | title = The Chicago Companion to Tocqueville's Democracy in America | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=poDsymzIrDoC | location = Chicago | publisher = University of Chicago Press | publication-date = 2012 | page = 82 | isbn = 9780226737058 | access-date = 2016-08-08 | quote = For Tocqueville ''individualism'' meant the habit of living isolated from your fellows, of not concerning yourself with any public affairs, and of abandoning those matters to the care of the government as the only clearly visible representative of common interests. Like democratic materialism, democratic individualism led to the death of civic life and opened the door to any despotic power that would assume responsibility for shared interests. [...] We need to recognize that Toqueville [..] treated the United States as something of an exception. He had described the American republic as shielded from the worst effects of democratic materialism; in his analysis, it was also insulated from individualism. }} </ref> Indeed, the [[United States Declaration of Independence]] and the [[US Constitution|Constitution]] explicitly raise the [[life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness |pursuit of happiness]] and the [[expectation of privacy]] to the level of [[rights]].{{Citation needed|date= December 2016}}
George Lakoff sees the [[metaphor]] of life as "a [[travel|journey]]" as a noteworthy structuring idea in "our culture".<ref> {{cite book | last1 = Lakoff | first1 = George | author-link1 = George Lakoff | orig-year = 1979 | chapter = Contemporary theory of metaphor | editor1-last = Ortony | editor1-first = Andrew | title = Metaphor and Thought | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=QiJRvuXA_VcC | location = Cambridge | publisher = Cambridge University Press | publication-date = 1993 | pages = 223–224 | isbn = 9780521405614 | access-date = 2016-08-08 | quote = Long-term, purposeful activities are journeys. [...] In our culture, life is assumed to be purposeful, that is, we are expected to have goals in life. In the event[-]structure metaphor, purposes are destinations and purposeful action is self-propelled motion towards a destination. A purposeful life is a journey. Goals in life are destinations on the journey. [...] Choosing a means to achieve a goal is choosing a path to destination. [...] [T]he love is a journey metaphor inherits the structure of the life is a journey metaphor. [...] a career is a journey. }} </ref> Compare the traditional Chinese concept of [[tao]].
In modern times, many people have come to think of their personal lives as separate from their [[working time | work]].<ref> {{cite book |last= Best |first= Shaun |title= Leisure Studies: Themes and Perspectives |year= 2009 |publisher= SAGE Publications |pages= 201 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=P8Pr8SYBmI8C&pg=PA201&dq=work+leisure#v=onepage&q=work%20leisure&f=false |isbn= 978-1-4129-0386-8 }} </ref>{{qn|date=October 2018}} This [[9 to 5]] paradigm regards work and [[recreation]] as distinct; one is either on the job or not, and the transition is abrupt. Employees have certain hours they are bound to work, and work during recreational time is rare. This may{{original research inline|date= August 2016}} reflect the continuing specialization of jobs and the demand for increased efficiency, both at work and at home. The common phrase "Work hard, play hard" illustrates this mindset. There is a growing{{quantify|date= August 2016}} trend, however, toward living more holistically and minimizing such rigid distinctions between work and play, in order to achieve an "appropriate" [[work–life balance]].{{citation needed|date= August 2016}}
The concept of personal life also tends to be associated{{by whom|date= August 2016}} with the [[clothing |way individuals dress]], the [[food |food they eat]], their [[education| schooling and further education]] as well as their [[hobbies]], [[leisure |leisure activities]], and [[performing arts| cultural interests]]. Increasingly, in the [[developed world]], a person's [[daily life]] is also influenced by leisure-time use of [[consumer electronics]] such as [[television]]s, [[computer]]s and the [[Internet]], [[mobile phone]]s and [[digital camera]]s.<ref name=Shah> {{cite web |last= Shah |first= Agam |title= Netbooks Propel Global Semiconductor Sales |url= http://www.pcworld.com/article/173052/netbooks_propel_global_semiconductor_sales.html |work= PCWorld |publisher= PCWorld Communications, Inc. |accessdate= 26 February 2011 }} </ref>{{qn|date= August 2016}}
Other factors affecting personal life include individuals' [[health]], [[interpersonal relationship |personal relationships]], [[pet]]s as well as [[home]] and [[personal possession]]s.{{citation needed|date= August 2016}}
==Leisure activities== [[File:Kabukicho at night 02.JPG|thumb|[[Kabukicho]] is [[Tokyo]]'s entertainment district.]] The way in which individuals make use of their spare time also plays an important role in defining their personal lives. In general, leisure activities can be categorised as either passive, in cases when no real effort is required, or active, when substantial physical or mental energy is needed.<ref name=Stebbins>{{cite journal|last=Stebbins|first=Robert A.|title=Choice and Experiential Definitions of Leisure|journal=LSA Newsletter|date=November 2002|volume=63|url=http://people.ucalgary.ca/~stebbins/reflections1.pdf}}</ref>
Passive activities include watching [[television]], listening to [[music]], watching sports activities or going to the [[movie theatre|cinema]]. The individual simply relaxes without any special effort.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}
Active activities may be more or less intensive ranging from [[walking]], through [[jogging]] and [[cycling]] to sports such as [[tennis]] or [[football]]. Playing [[chess]] or undertaking creative writing might also be considered as demanding as these require a fair amount of mental effort.{{Citation needed|date=December 2016}}
Based on 2007 data, a US survey on use of leisure time found that the daily use of leisure time by individuals over 15 averaged 4.9 hours. Of this, more than half (2.6 hours) went on watching TV while only 19 minutes involved active participation in sports and exercise.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leisure Time on an Average Day|url=http://www.bls.gov/tus/charts/leisure.htm|work=American Time Use Survey|publisher=Bureau of Labor Statistics|accessdate=26 February 2011}}</ref>
==Privacy== [[File:Roscheid Hunsrückhaus innen.jpg|thumb|The room often reflects many aspects of one's personal life.]] [[Privacy]] has been understood as entailing two different concepts; namely [[informational privacy]] and decisional privacy. The former concerns the right to be left alone in respect of the most intimate details of one's personal life and is a more accepted doctrine than the latter which concerns freedom from undue regulation and control.<ref name=privacy>{{cite book|last=Kumar|first=Krishna|title=Public and private in thought and practice : perspectives on a grand dichotomy|year=997|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago; London|isbn=0-226-88624-7|pages=383|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
